<br>
1.)  Verbs do conjugate, but not like in English or any other European language that I'm familiar with.  English verbs conjugate differently depending upon tense and subject, Japanese verbs conjugatation depends on tense but as far as subjects are concerned things get more complicated.  <br>
<br>
If you've studied French, Italian, Spanish or most of the other garden variety European languages you probably have come across the fact that subjects are seperated roughly into about 6 categories: I, you (you all), thou (you informal), he/she/one, they, we.  English usually only has different conjugations for he/she/one, if there are any differences at all, e.g.<br>
   I say ..... You say ... She says  .... They say  .... We say<br>
But there are A LOT of discrepancies.  French is more regular and Italian/Latin more regular still.<br>
<br>
Ok so that's background ... Japanese is totally different.  Given a subject from any one of those categories, the conjugation of the Japanese verb is exactly the same.  That's the good part, the bad part is that in Japanese choosing which verb to use often depends heavily upon the subject.  The simplest example is iru and aru.  Both mean &quot;to be&quot;, but iru is used for animate objects (with a few exceptions), and aru is used for inanimate objects (also with a few exceptions). That's just the tip of the iceberg though, there is are large sets of words to be used depending on various social situations, and lots of other problematic complications.  Anyway, its a headache.<br>
<br>
Moreover, Japanese does a lot more with verb conjugation than English.  For example the -tara conjugation of a verb V means &quot;if V then ...&quot;.  That also is just one of many examples.<br>
<br>
2.) Do you mean like upper and lower case?  If so, then no.  They have three alphabets and that's plenty, no need to through any more in.<br>
<br>
3.)  Tense conjugation is primarily broken down into perfect (completed action) and imperfect (incomplete action).  Past tense falls into the perfect category and both future and present come under imperfect.  This can get confusing sometimes but usually context easily differentiates the two.  There are also &quot;continual&quot; tenses (at least that's what I call them, I'm not sure what the linguistically correct name is).  For example &quot;I am typing&quot; and &quot;I was sleeping&quot; are both sentences that express a continuing action, even though one is perfect and the other imperfect.  That's pretty much it. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=superflat>superflat</A> at: 9/27/02 12:48:43 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/umaimaipanda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/27/02 2:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=936.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/images/hikkoshi.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: nashi</span><hr size=1> as superflat mentioned, your questions are very complex.  <br>
